# The mound is constructed at a **coastal** location, typically on **elevated** ground, making it visible from the sea and situated at a key point along maritime transportation routes. # These kofun are **not** located near **alluvial plains** suitable for **wet rice cultivation**, distinguishing them from inland burial mounds that were closely tied to agricultural economies. # They are among the **largest kofun** in their respective regions. (This trend also applies to other mound shapes, such as large-scale **round kofun**.) # They appear **fully developed** in the early **{{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代}} (4th century)**, featuring **tiered mound construction (段築構造)**, **haniwa rows (埴輪列)**, and **stone facing (葺石)**. # These kofun **suddenly appear** in regions with no previous history of large burial mounds. The ruling lineage associated with them typically lasts **only one or two generations**, meaning that either a **single mound** or, at most, **two kofun** are built before the lineage disappears. In some cases, there is a **gap in time before a new ruling lineage emerges**. # They exhibit **regional clustering**, with prominent examples found along Japan’s coastline.
In **Western Japan**, these kofun appear along the **eastern and western coasts of Kyushu (九州)**, **the Seto Inland Sea (瀬戸内海)**, and **Osaka Bay (大阪湾)**. In **Eastern Japan**, they are found along **Tokyo Bay (東京湾)**, the **former Katori Sea (香取海)**, and the **Pacific coastline of the Tōhoku region (東北地方)**. Given their **high visibility from the sea** and strategic locations near **inlets and capes**, these tombs are thought to have belonged to rulers who controlled **maritime trade and navigation**. Additionally, because they often appear in regions without a previous tradition of mound-building and vanish quickly, it is speculated that **their construction was heavily influenced by the central authority of the Yamato state (ヤマト王権)**.{{Sfn|Hirose|2015|pp=21-25}}
The archaeologist {{ill|Nishikawa Shūichi|ja|西川修一}} notes that the concept of "Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun" is **more specific** than broader terms like **"Marine Kofun" (海の古墳)**, which includes **other types of tombs** such as **box-shaped stone cist tombs (箱式石棺墓)**.{{Sfn|Nishikawa|2018|p=3}}
