ed to agricultural economies. # They are among the '''largest kofun''' in their respective regions. (This trend also applies to other mound shapes, such as large-scale '''round kofun'''.) # They appear '''fully developed''' in the early '''{{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}} (4th century)''', featuring '''tiered mound construction (段築構造)''', '''[[haniwa]] rows (埴輪列)''', and [[Fukiishi]] '''(葺石)'''. # These kofun '''suddenly appear''' in regions with no previous history of large Kofuns. The ruling lineage associated with them typically lasts '''only one or two generations''', meaning that either a '''single mound''' or, at most, '''two kofun''' are built before the lineage disappears. In some cases, there is a '''gap in time before a new ruling lineage emerges'''. # They exhibit '''regional clustering''', with prominent examples found along Japan’s coastline. In '''Western Japan''', these kofun appear along the '''eastern and western coasts of Kyushu (九州)''', '''the Seto Inland Sea (瀬戸内海)''', and '''Osaka Bay (大阪湾)'''. In '''Eastern Japan''', they are found along '''Tokyo Bay (東京湾)''', the '''former Katori Sea (香取海)''', and the '''Pacific coastline of the Tōhoku region (東北地方)'''. Given their '''high visibility from the sea''' and strategic locations near '''inlets and capes''', these tombs are thought to have belonged to rulers who controlled '''maritime trade and navigation'''. Additionally, because they often appear in regions without a previous tradition of mound-building and vanish quickly, it is speculated that '''their construction was heavily influenced by the central authority of the [[Yamato Kingship|Yamato state]] (ヤマト王権)'''.{{Sfn|Hirose|2015|pp=21-25}} The archaeologist {{ill|Nishikawa Shūichi|ja|西川修一|12=draft}} notes that the concept of "Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun" is '''more specific''' than broader terms like '''"Marine Kofun" (海の古墳)''', which includes '''other types of tombs''' such as '''box-shaped stone cist tombs (箱式石棺墓)'''.{{Sfn|Nishikawa|2018|p=3}} == Notable Examples == * {{ill|Myōkensan Kofun|ja|妙見山古墳 (今治市)|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ōnishi, Imabari|ja|今治市大西町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Goshikizuka Kofun|ja|五色塚古墳|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tarumi-ku, Kobe|ja|神戸市垂水区|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Amino Chōshiyama Kofun|ja|網野銚子山古墳|12=draft}} ({{ill|Kyōtango|ja|京丹後市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Nagae-Sakurayama Kofun Cluster|ja|長柄桜山古墳群|12=draft}} ({{ill|Zushi, Kanagawa|ja|逗子市|12=draft}} / {{ill|Hayama, Kanagawa|ja|三浦郡葉山町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Dairizuka Kofun Cluster|ja|内裏塚古墳群|12=draft}} ({{ill|Futtsu, Chiba|ja|富津市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Anesaki Futagozuka Kofun|lt=Anegasaki Kofun Cluster|ja|姉崎古墳群|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ichihara, Chiba|ja|市原市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Isohama Kofun Cluster|ja|磯浜古墳群|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ōarai, Ibaraki|ja|東茨城郡大洗町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県|12=draft}}) == References == {{Reflist}} == Bibliography == *{{Cite book|和書|last=広瀬|first=和雄|authorlink=広瀬和雄|editor=公益財団法人{{ill|Kanagawa Archaeology Foundation|ja|かながわ考古学財団|12=draft}}|title=海浜型前方後円墳の時代|publisher={{ill|Dōsei-sha|ja|同成社|12=draft}}|year=2015|date=2015-03-31|isbn=9784886216922|ref=harv}} *{{Cite book|和書|last=西川|first=修一|editor={{ill|Kanagawa Prefectural Buried Cultural Properties Center|ja|神奈川県埋蔵文化財センター|12=draft}}|title=平成30th year （2018th year ）度第6回考古学講座・古墳時代の海洋民について|series=神奈川県埋蔵文化財センター考古学講座配布資料|publisher={{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture Board of Education|ja|神奈川県教育委員会|12=draft}}|year=2018|date=2018-12-22|url=https://www.pref.kanagawa.jp/docs/ar3/cnt/f6656/p893306.html|ref=harv}} == See Also == * {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}} * {{ill|Archaeology|ja|考古学|12=draft}}
