[[File:Goshiki-zuka Kofun, zenpoubu-2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{ill|Akashi Strait|ja|明石海峡|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} overlooking {{ill|Goshikizuka Kofun|ja|五色塚古墳|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tarumi-ku, Kobe|ja|神戸市垂水区|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}})]]
'''{{ill|Coastal Zenpokoenfun|ja|海浜型前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''' (海浜型前方後円墳) refers to a subset of {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the predominant Kofun type of the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, that were deliberately constructed at the tips of {{ill|Ria coast|ja|リアス式海岸|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} formations, {{ill|Marine terrace|ja|海岸段丘|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} edges, or {{ill|Beach ridge|ja|浜堤|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} zones. These tombs were positioned along coastlines with excellent visibility from the sea. The concept was proposed by the archaeologist {{ill|Hirose Kazuo|ja|広瀬和雄|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} between 2013 and 2015.{{Sfn|Nishikawa|2018|p=3|qq=}}
== Overview ==
It was previously recognized that some {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} were built facing the sea. However, during a 2013 symposium titled *The Age of Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun*, organized by the {{ill|Kanagawa Archaeology Foundation|ja|かながわ考古学財団|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hirose Kazuo|ja|広瀬和雄|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} introduced the term '''"Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun"''' and further defined its characteristics. The symposium’s findings were later published as a general reference book in 2015.{{Sfn|Hirose|2015|qq=}}
{{ill|Hirose Kazuo|ja|広瀬和雄|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} outlined the following defining conditions for a '''Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun''':{{Sfn|Hirose|2015|pp=1-31|qq=}}
# The mound is constructed at a '''coastal''' location, typically on '''elevated''' ground, making it visible from the sea and situated at a key point along maritime transportation routes.
# These kofun are '''not''' located near '''[[:en:Alluvial_plains|alluvial plains]]''' suitable for {{ill|Rice Cultivation|ja|稲作|lt=wet rice cultivation|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, distinguishing them from inland Kofuns that were closely tied to agricultural economies.
# They are among the '''largest kofun''' in their respective regions. (This trend also applies to other mound shapes, such as large-scale '''round kofun'''.)
# They appear '''fully developed''' in the early '''{{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (4th century)''', featuring '''tiered mound construction (段築構造)''', '''[[haniwa]] rows (埴輪列)''', and [[Fukiishi]] '''(葺石)'''.
# These kofun '''suddenly appear''' in regions with no previous history of large Kofuns. The ruling lineage associated with them typically lasts '''only one or two generations''', meaning that either a '''single mound''' or, at most, '''two kofun''' are built before the lineage disappears. In some cases, there is a '''gap in time before a new ruling lineage emerges'''.
# They exhibit '''regional clustering''', with prominent examples found along Japan’s coastline.
In '''Western Japan''', these kofun appear along the '''eastern and western coasts of Kyushu (九州)''', '''the Seto Inland Sea (瀬戸内海)''', and '''Osaka Bay (大阪湾)'''. In '''Eastern Japan''', they are found along '''Tokyo Bay (東京湾)''', the '''former Katori Sea (香取海)''', and the '''Pacific coastline of the Tōhoku region (東北地方)'''. Given their '''high visibility from the sea''' and strategic locations near '''inlets and capes''', these tombs are thought to have belonged to rulers who controlled '''maritime trade and navigation'''. Additionally, because they often appear in regions without a previous tradition of mound-building and vanish quickly, it is speculated that '''their construction was heavily influenced by the central authority of the [[Yamato Kingship|Yamato state]] (ヤマト王権)'''.{{Sfn|Hirose|2015|pp=21-25|qq=}}
The archaeologist {{ill|Nishikawa Shūichi|ja|西川修一|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} notes that the concept of "Coastal Keyhole-shaped Kofun" is '''more specific''' than broader terms like '''"Marine Kofun" (海の古墳)''', which includes '''other types of tombs''' such as '''box-shaped stone cist tombs (箱式石棺墓)'''.{{Sfn|Nishikawa|2018|p=3|qq=}}
